<dl id="un1013ag"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="un1" href="#un1013">UN1: </a>  <a href="../../ff/unbs/un1all.htm#un1013ag"> (NLI.3) 13(ag)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Ophites adorers of serpent (of wisdom) Logos.</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">A Study in Christian Gnosticism&rdquo; 330: The inner tradition that underlay the crude notions handed on to us by the Church Fathers as the teaching of Cerinthus, is more clearly apparent from what Iren&aelig;us tells us of the doctrines of those whom he calls <mark>Ophites (= Worshippers of the Serpent,&mdash;that is, as they themselves declared, of the Serpent of Wisdom, the Logos)</mark>, but who called themselves simply Gnostics, and whom Theodoret calls Sethians. <small> <a name="THRdec1908" href="/udra/udex.htm#thrdec1908"><cite title="source">The Theosophical Review</cite></a> (December 1908), G. R. S. Mead, &ldquo;The Secret of Jesus</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c07257f" href="../../../f/ff/fnbs/c07all.htm#c07257f">VI.C.07:257(f)</a>, <a name="c07257g" href="../../../f/ff/fnbs/c07all.htm#c07257g">VI.C.07:257(g)</a> </dd> </dd></dl>
